[00:02] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: '[music] Hi, welcome to another video. So, Alibaba\'s Tongi Lab just dropped something pretty interesting. It\'s called fun audio chat, and it\'s'

[00:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basically a large audio language model built for natural, low latency voice conversations. Think of it like having a conversation with an AI, but instead of typing, you just talk to it and it talks back in'

[00:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'real time. Now, we\'ve seen voice models before. Open AAI has their voice mode. Google has Gemini Live. There\'s a bunch of'

[00:40] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'options, but most of them are cloud-based, which means latency, API costs, and you\'re sending your voice data to someone else\'s servers. Fun Audio Chat is fully open source,'

[00:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'runs locally, and it\'s surprisingly efficient. Let me explain why that efficiency matters. They\'ve got this dual resolution approach where the main processing runs at just 5 hertz instead'

[01:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'of the usual 12.5 Hz or 25 Hz that other models use. That might sound like a small technical detail, but it cuts GPU usage by about 50%.'

[01:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'which is pretty significant if you\'re running this stuff locally. The way it works is they have a shared backbone that runs at the low 5 herz rate for most of the heavy lifting and then a'

[01:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'refined head that operates at 25 hertz just for the final speech output. So you get the quality of a highresolution model with the computational cost of a lowresolution'

[01:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'one. That\'s a clever engineering trade-off. Let me break down what this model can actually do. First, you\'ve got voice empathy. The model can detect emotional context through things like tone, pace,'

[02:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and procity. So, if you sound frustrated, it picks up on that and responds appropriately. If you sound excited, it matches that energy. So, I asked it something here.'

[02:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Here\'s that recording. Hey, I recently fell and fractured my right arm. Do you think it will get better? &gt;&gt; I know how bad it might feel, but don\'t worry. Most fractured arms heal fast.'

[02:28] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You should always consult with your doctor for the best practices, but generally taking medicines on time, reducing fatigue, and getting better sleep is beneficial. &gt;&gt; Then I asked it again, but told it to be'

[02:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'motivating. So, this is the recording. Hey, I fractured my right arm. Can you cheer me up? &gt;&gt; I\'d tell you that you\'re going to be all right, but strictly speaking, right now'

[02:53] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you\'re mostly left. [laughter] Honestly, you should have just told us you wanted to get out of doing the dishes. You didn\'t have to go to such extreme lengths. &gt;&gt; That\'s kind of cool for more natural'

[03:06] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interactions. It\'s not just listening to your words, it\'s listening to how you say them. Second, there\'s speech instruction following. You can give it complex voice commands to control how it responds.'

[03:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Things like emotion, speaking style, speed, pitch, and volume. So, you can literally tell it to speak faster or sound more excited, and it adjusts.'

[03:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You could say, "Respond like you\'re explaining this to a 5-year-old or speak with more enthusiasm." And it actually follows those instructions. Here\'s something that I'

[03:45] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tried. Hey, I am running a promo at my shop where people will get two pair of socks for the price of one. Can you speak like a loud salesman on a megaphone? &gt;&gt; Um, okay, everyone. We are selling two'

[03:57] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'socks for just the price of one. Yes, you heard that right. Two socks for the price of one. Just one. The offer only lasts for today. Get it now. Did you'

[04:11] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'like that? Want me to change something? &gt;&gt; That level of control is pretty useful. Third, and this is interesting, it supports speech function calling.'

[04:23] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Basically, you can give it natural voice commands to execute tasks. So, instead of clicking buttons or typing commands, you just tell it what to do, which is pretty amazing for hands-free workflows.'

[04:37] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Imagine building a voice controlled assistant that can actually trigger actions in your applications. That\'s what this enables. Fourth, there\'s general audio'

[04:49] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'understanding. It can do speech transcription, identify sound sources, and even classify music genres. So, it\'s not just about conversations. It understands audio in a broader sense.'

[05:03] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'You could play it a clip and ask what\'s happening in the audio and it can describe it. That opens up a lot of possibilities for audio analysis tools. And fifth, you\'ve got full duplex'

[05:17] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interaction. This means you can interrupt it mid-sentence and it handles natural turn taking like a real conversation. No more waiting for it to finish before you can speak.'

[05:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'This is actually harder to implement than it sounds because the model needs to continuously listen while it\'s generating speech. Most voice assistants don\'t handle this'

[05:42] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'well. So, it\'s nice to see it built in here. Now, let\'s talk about the benchmarks because this is where it gets impressive. Fun Audio Chat ranks top tier on'

[05:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'basically every major audio benchmark. Open audio bench, voice bench, ultra evil audio for spoken QA, MMA AU, MMA AU pro and MMSU for audio understanding,'

[06:07] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'speech Abbench, speech BFCL, and Speech Smart Interact for function calling, and V style for instruction following. So, it\'s not just good at one thing. It\'s'

[06:19] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'competitive across the board. That\'s rare for an open-source model. Usually you see models that excel in one area but fall behind in others. Fun audio chat seems to be a genuine'

[06:32] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'allrounder. Now if you want to run this yourself, here\'s what you need. The model requires about 24 GB of GPU memory for inference. If you\'re training, you\'ll need 4x 80'

[06:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'gigs of GPUs. So that\'s more of a serious setup. But for just running it locally and testing it out, a good consumer GPU should work. An RTX 490 or a 3090 with 24 GB would be the sweet'

[07:04] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'spot. You might be able to squeeze it onto smaller GPUs with some optimization, but I haven\'t tested that. For software, you need Python 3.12,'

[07:18] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'PyTorch 2.8.0, zero ffmpeg and a Qday 12.8 compatible environment. To install it, you clone the repo with subm'

[07:30] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'modules, create a cond environment with Python 3.12, install PyTorch with the CUDA 12.8 wheel, and then pip install the requirements. Pretty standard stuff.'

[07:43] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Then you download two pre-trained models from hugging face or model scope, the main fun audio chat 8B model and a smaller fun cozy voice 3 model for speech synthesis.'

[07:56] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The cozy voice model is what actually generates the audio output. So you need both for the full experience. Once that\'s done, you can run the example scripts. There\'s infer S2T'

[08:09] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Python file for speechtoext and infer S2S Python file for full speechtospech interactions. They also have a web-based interface if'

[08:21] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'you want something more visual. You run the server component, fire up the React client, and you\'ve got a proper chat interface for voice conversations. You do need node and SSL certificates'

[08:34] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'for that, but it\'s all documented in the repo. The web interface is nice because you can see the conversation history and it feels more like a proper application.'

[08:46] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'Now, let me talk about some use cases where this makes sense. If you\'re building a voice assistant for a specific domain, like customer service or technical support, having an'

[09:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'open-source model you can fine-tune is huge. You can train it on your company\'s knowledge base and deploy it without ongoing API costs. If you\'re working on accessibility'

[09:14] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'tools, the combination of speech to text, text to speech, and audio understanding in one model is really powerful. You could build tools that help people'

[09:26] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'interact with computers entirely through voice. And if you\'re just experimenting with voice AI for fun, this is a great playground. No API keys, no usage limits. Just download and start'

[09:41] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'building. Now I should mention the limitations. The developers themselves say the model can hallucinate and generate inaccurate responses especially in complex scenarios.'

[09:54] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'The full duplex mode is still experimental. And while 24 GB is manageable for inference, it\'s still not something you can run on a laptop. So take it with a grain of salt and don\'t expect'

[10:08] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'perfection. But overall, this is pretty impressive work. An 8B parameter model that can handle natural voice conversations with low latency, emotional understanding,'

[10:20] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'and function calling. That\'s a lot of capability in a relatively compact package. The fact that it\'s open- source under Apache 2.0 is great, too. You can actually run this locally,'

[10:35] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'modify it, and integrate it into your own projects. No API costs, no rate limits, just your own hardware. That\'s the kind of AI development I like'

[10:47] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'to see. If you\'re into voice, AI, or building applications that need natural speech interaction, fun audio chat is definitely worth checking out. The GitHub repo has all the code and the'

[11:00] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'demo page has audio samples so you can hear what it sounds like. Overall, it\'s pretty cool. Anyway, share your thoughts below and subscribe to the channel. You'

[11:12] [scene:talk]
VISUAL:
AUDIO: 'can also donate via Superthanks option or join the channel as [music] well and get some perks. I\'ll see you in the next video. Bye.'
